  "flag_name": "WebRTC-HeaderExtensionNegotiateMemory (WebRTC field trial)",
  "finch_name": null,
  "non_finch_justification": "The change is in webrtc, so it uses WebRTC field trials which provide the same functionality as finch flags in practice (including the ability to do Finch experiments/kill switches)",
  "ongoing_constraints": null,
  "rollout_plan": 0,
  "rollout_plan_displayname": "Will ship enabled for all users",
  "motivation": "During development of the L4S congestion control feature, which is the first time we've tried to use this API to turn off a feature, it was discovered that the current definition was very unergonomic for this case.\n\nThe change in https://github.com/w3c/webrtc-extensions/pull/238 is believed to not change the behavior for current users, but will make the behavior much more ergonomic for this particular use case.",
  "devtrial_instructions": null,
  "activation_risks": null,
  "measurement": null,
  "availability_expectation": "The base spec being modified is only available in Chromium browsers so far. Given support from other vendors in WG, we expect that when others ship this, they will conform to the modified spec.",
  "adoption_expectation": "Feature will be used by partners utilizing WebRTC advanced features.",
  "adoption_plan": "Feature will be used in the rollout of L4S congestion control in Meet, with other interactive video products expected to follow.",
  "initial_public_proposal_url": null,
  "explainer_links": [],
  "requires_embedder_support": false,
  "spec_link": "https://w3c.github.io/webrtc-extensions/#rtp-header-extension-control-modifications",
  "api_spec": true,
  "automation_spec": false,
  "interop_compat_risks": "This API has been used up to now to turn on behavior (in the form of RTP header extensions) on the RTP connection that was shipped as off-by-default. \nWhat will change is that when features that are on by default are turned off in negotiation, they will remain off in subsequent negotiation rounds.\nWe don't believe that anyone has actively used it to turn off features.\n\nIn case someone has previously tried, 3 cases, 2 of which are harmless:\n\n- The responder does not support the feature, and therefore always replies with \"feature off\". Result is that it will not be turned on - no change.\n- The responder supports the feature, but has rejected it in initial negotiation because it does not want to use it. Under previous behavior, it would have to respond to all subsequent negotiation rounds by turning off the feature again. Under the new behavior, it will already be off .\n\nThe abnormal case:\n\n- The responder supports the feature, but has rejected it in initial negotiation because it does not want to use it, but does not have code to turn it off in subsequent negotiation. The change will turn it on.\n\nSo we think that this change brings no change to expected behavior for current users, and if the hypothetical user that turns off features using this API exists, it is more likely to fix an undetected bug in their code than to introduce undesired behavior.",
  "all_platforms": true,
  "all_platforms_descr": null,
  "non_oss_deps": null,
  "anticipated_spec_changes": "All spec changes merged.",
  "security_risks": null,
  "ergonomics_risks": null,
  "wpt": true,
  "wpt_descr": "webrtc-extensions/RTCRtpTransceiver-headerExtensionControl.html will be affected by the spec change. A test update will be shipped together with enabling the feature.\n\nwpt.fyi link: https://wpt.fyi/results/webrtc-extensions/RTCRtpTransceiver-headerExtensionControl.html\n",
  "webview_risks": "Low risk. Protected by WebRTC field trial \"WebRTC-HeaderExtensionNegotiateMemory\".",
